==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|la}} ''[[depretiare]]'', ''[[depreciare]]'', to depreciate, from ''[[de-#Latin|de-]]'' + ''[[pretium]]'', price

===Verb===
{{en-verb|depreciat|ing}}

# {{intransitive}} To reduce in value over time.
# {{transitive}} To [[belittle]]

====Synonyms====
* (''reduce in value over time''):
* (''belittle''): [[do down]]

====Antonyms====
* (''reduce in value over time''): [[appreciate]]
* (''belittle''): [[aggrandise]]/[[aggrandize]], [[big up]] {{qualifier|slang}}

====Translations====
{{trans-top|To reduce in value over time}}
* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|обезценявам}}
{{trans-mid}}
* Finnish: {{t+|fi|laskea}}
* French: {{t|fr|déprécier}}
{{trans-bottom}}

{{trans-top|To [[belittle]]}}
* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|подценявам}}
{{trans-mid}}
* Finnish: {{t-|fi|vähätellä}}, {{t-|fi|väheksyä}}
{{trans-bottom}}

====Usage notes====
* Do not confuse with '''[[deprecate]]''', which means 'to disapprove of'. The meaning of ''deprecate'' has lately been [[encroach]]ing on ''depreciate'' in the sense 'to belittle'.

